  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Can potentially increase to 30 years if the laundering involves specific criminal proceeds\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Additional potential consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Criminal record\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Professional license revocation\n- Enhanced scrutiny from financial regulators\n\nThese penalties can vary based on specific circumstances like transaction amount, intent, and prior criminal history. Prosecution typically occurs through statutes like the Money Laundering Control Act and Bank Secrecy Act.\n\nThe exact penalties depend on the specific details of the case and are determined by federal prosecutors and judges. Consulting a qualified legal professional would provide the most precise information for a specific situation.",
